Title: Old Newgate Mine
Log:
I made a trip out here in April 2007 but the mine and prison weren't open. It's such a cool place though so I had to return. I really enjoyed the history and the tour of the mine. I can't believe what awful conditions the prisoners lived in. It was so dark and dank and WET. Ugh. I'd have a really hard time living under those conditions.

Interestingly, you got a life sentence here for attempted rape but only just over a year for attempted murder. Times have changed. I also learned that not only could you be branded with an "A" for adultery but also a "B" to your forehead for burglary and a "C" for...heck, I can't remember. Point is, the Puritans wanted you embarassed for the rest of your life.

Thanks for a great earthcache!
title: Old Newgate Mine

Title: Old Newgate Mine
Log:
Really, really enjoyed touring the prison and the mine. I was amazed how wet the mine was! Wear a hat. And boots. The walls run with water, the ceiling drips with it. It hasn't rained much lately, so that has to be just the way it is (where does all that water come from? It's not below the water table). Gave it a deeply creepy ambience. I can't believe human beings could sleep down that hole for years and not die of pneumonia.

I'll log this and upload my photo now. If I get the question wrong, let me know and I'll biff this log. Meanwhile, thank you very much for a MOST enjoyable earthcache!

Title: Marengo Cave
Log: N9TDC & I went on a two-day excursion to Southern Indiana over the weekend of February 6th & 7th. Our destination was Harmonist Labyrinth, which has been a four+ year goal of ours, & marking Posey County & 12 additional counties off of our 2010 caching to-do list. As customary, we got sidetracked along the way, but we did manage to find caches in about a half-dozen or so counties. We had such a fantastic journey, which is what geocaching is all about - having an extraordinary time, finding fascinating places & things, learning a little geology, bonding & creating memories. Seeing N9TDC's face light up as he reminisced in Evansville & Vincennes, towns he once called home, & listening to him talk to old friends on his ham radio were reasons enough to take the trip - everything else we saw & did was icing on the cake! We went to breakfast at one of N9TDC's favorite spots, the Kat-A-Corner, in Sullivan, Indiana, visited the breathtaking labyrinth in New Harmony, went to an awesome old cemetery & Harmonie State Park, drove by N9TDC's very first apartment, got glazed, went to the Casino Aztar (which was, by far, the low point in our trip!), ate dinner at N9TDC's favorite early 1990's hang out, the Nisbet Inn in Haubstadt, Indiana, did a little fossil hunting, took a 70-minute tour of the awesome Marengo Cave (which was, by far, the high point in our trip!), saw a curious chainsaw garden which is featured in the book, Weird Indiana (well deserved) & a limestone kiln & walked a short way along the Knobstone Trail. I am glad I wasn't able to read all of Cav Scout's Marengo Cave description until after our visit, because I'm pretty sure I wouldn't have trekked anywhere in the dark that was the home of cave rats! Thank you so much to all of the cache owners for putting out &/or creating your caches. You gave me the type of weekend that I believe weekends were made for! I apologize for logging all of our cache finds on the 7th! >:( / 0:-)

Title: MACA: Green River at Mammoth Cave
Log: We enjoyed our visit to Mammoth Cave National Park today. Since we had gone down in the caves on a prior visit, we spent the afternoon hiking! We did an expanded loop that included nabbing two other earthcaches! It was a long, steamy hike but well worth it. The trail was great, the forest beautiful, and the views of the river were an added bonus. Thank you so much for this interesting cache. I enjoyed learning more about the Green River.

Log:
Konnarock and I could not have picked a more gorgeous day for a visit to Cave Spring. The last time I was here it was cold and miserable. Today was much warmer owing largely I'm sure, to the hot air emanating from my caching pardner.

I actually arrived at ground zero a few steps ahead of KK in spite of his bionic leg with which he can leap tall ammo boxes in a single bound. But, being the Christmas season I shared FTF with him.

Thanks for a well done and much appreciated Earth Cache, and a very Merry and Happy New Year to everyone.
title: Cave Springs Earth Cache

Title: Cave Springs Earth Cache
Log:
It was a nice day to hike from the gated entrance of the Park to be FTFs on this fine EC. I flew in with the old buzzard, Papafuz. The last time we did this, it was snowing and pretty cold. We did a little CITO at the Cave entrance, but generally the area was clean and just like mother nature intended it.
I want to set the record straight. Just because Papafuz was first to have his picture taken at the Cave entrance doesn't mean he can to be the only FTF! He rushed up to the entrance just to see if any of his bat cousins were present! Much to his disappointment, there weren't any bats there but I think he enjoyed himself anyway!
Thanks for all of your work and allowing two old coots to have a lot of fun. Merry Christmas and have a wonderful earthcaching New Year!

Title: Delaware Mine
Log:
I just returned from a 5 day loop around Michigans Upper Peninsula and also spent an afternoon in Sault Saint Marie, Ontario. The weather started out at 86 degrees and muggy. As the week progressed it cooled to 72 and fresh. I concentrated on EarthCaches and Virtuals and attempted to fill in more of my D/T matrix as well as all UP counties. I progressed from St. Ignace to the Soo, Pictured Rocks, Marquette, Houghton and the Keweenaw. Then I moved on to the Porcupine Mountains and along the southern edge of the peninsula from Ironwood back to the Straits. I spent 4 nights camping at our clean and beautiful state parks and averaged 24 caches per day for a total of 121.

I enjoyed this little stop along the way. I was fun and interesting to pick through the tailings. Thank you for the learning experience and maintaining your EarthCache. I enjoyed it very much. The Answers have been e-mailed. TFTF

Title: Martins Head Sea Cave
Log: This was an awesome spot, not so much fun getting there, the roads were horrible, thick soupy mud, from the snow last week no doubt, the truck was fish tailing the whole way, the walk through the path and the woods was nice on the way there but was pretty much raining cats and dogs on the way back. We were there about 3 hours before low tide, and that was plenty, we had tons of time to explore, My wife was cold and wet so we called our exploring short, speaking of shorts the temp was perfect for an aggressive hike up and down the mountain, Thanks for bringing us here, beautiful. OH YA we saw a huge moose and a large owl just feet from us.
title: Martins Head Sea Cave

Title: Martins Head Sea Cave
Log:
Well there was about 6 inchs of snow on the road down there, very very poor road for my lil Nissan Versa but my studded snowtires held firm. We got hung up once, and I had to jack up the car and chop away the ice so we could continue. Made it to the parking spot which was around 750m from the cave. Bushwacked down to a quad trail and walked the rest of the ways. Awesome beach and our dog had fun running free. Cave was smaller than we expected but still very cool to see and witness the power of water first hand.

A very peaceful spot with just the sound of the water rolling in. Very enjoyable trip. Thanks.

Title: Dorchester Copper Mine
Log:
[font=Verdana]Oh, this was really an adventure. First, when I was driving where my navigation system told me to drive, I was very afraid to get stuck with the car in the mud. It was a standard rent car, not a suv.
When the navigation system told we that I have to find the rest of the way somewhere off road, it was about 300m to go. There was no way through the forest, it was raining, everthing was wet. But I wanted to find the mine so I went through the forest with the help of my GPS. As you can see on the picture, I found it.
And I had not forget to store the position of my car into the GPS before going to the mine, so I found my way back to the car.
I was wet when I was back at my car but happy to have seen the mine, seriously a place which is not very often visited by tourist. Thank you fo showing me that place.
[font=Comic Sans MS][size=3][b][blue]FamWei [/blue] [/b] [size=2] says thank you for this Cache.[/size][font=Verdana][size=1]
